<section xml:id="sec_transformations_of_graphs">
  <title>Transformations of Graphs</title>
  <subsection>
    <title>Recommended Tutorials:</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          \nameref{chp:plotting_functions}, pg.
          <xref ref="chp_plotting_functions"></xref>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          \nameref{chp:assignment_operator}, pg.
          <xref ref="chp_assignment_operator"></xref>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <p>
      In this activity,
      you will plot multiple functions at once to investigate basic transformations of functions.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises:</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plot the graphs of <m>\sin (x)</m> and
          <m>\cos (x)</m> on the same set of axes.
          Use <em>red</em> for <m>\sin (x)</m> and
          <em>blue</em> for <m>\cos (x)</m>.
          <aside>
            <p>
              If you do not specify the <m>x</m>-axis interval, Maple will default to increments of <m>\pi/8</m> from <m>-2\pi</m> to <m>2\pi</m>.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                By what amount do you need to shift the graph of <m>\sin (x)</m> <em>to the left</em>
                (negative <m>x</m> direction)
                so that it coincides with the graph of <m>\cos (x)</m>?
                Answer the question in sentence form by using the <image width="4%" source="images/new_text.png"/> button to create a new paragraph after the current line.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    An example of plotting multiple functions at once can be found on <xref ref="sec_plotting_multiple_functions">page</xref>.
                  </p>
                </aside>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By what amount do you need to shift the graph of
                <m>\sin (x)</m> <em>to the right</em>
                (positive <m>x</m> direction)
                so that it coincides with the graph of <m>\cos (x)</m>?
                Write your answer in sentence form using a new paragraph.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graphs of <m>{ e}^x</m> and <m>\ln(x)</m> should appear to be reflected over the line <m>y=x</m>.
          Plot all three graphs on the same axes using <c>linestyle=[solid,solid,dash</c>].
            <idx><h>plot</h><h>line style</h></idx>
        <aside>
            <p>
              The <c>exp(x)</c> function is the exponential function,
              <m>{ e}^x</m>.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <aside>
            <p>
              When plotting functions of the form <m>y=f(x)</m> using the <c>plot()</c> command,
              we omit the <m>y=</m>.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <aside>
            <p>
              When assigning the function to <m>f(x)</m>,
              use the <m>:=</m> operator.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>assignment operator</h></idx>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Assign the function <m>f(x) = \sqrt{-x^2 + 4x + 21}</m>.
          Plot each of the following functions on the same set of axes:
          <me>
            y = f(x), \, y = f(2x), \, y = 3f(x), \, y = f(-x), \, y = -f(x)
          </me>.
          Make sure that the graph is displayed with constrained scaling
          (<m>1:1</m>).
          Describe each transformation.
          Write your answer using a new paragraph.
          <aside>
            <p>
              An example of plotting transformations of a function can be found on <xref ref="subsec_plotting_transformations">page</xref>.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <aside>
            <p>
              It is always a good practice to specify the colours of multiple graphs in order to tell them apart.
              A list of plot colours can be found by typing <c>?colours</c> on a new Maple input.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>plot</h><h>colours</h></idx>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plot each of the following graphs separately:
          <aside>
            <p>
              The absolute value function <m>|\cdot|</m> in Maple is denoted as <c>abs( )</c>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>absolute value</h></idx>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y = \sin(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y = \sin(|x|)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y = |\sin(x)|</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        Create a new paragraph to describe the transformations of
        <m>y = \sin(x)</m> in parts (b) and (c).
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
</section>